Lately I've been hitting a wall with my playgroup, how do you mitigate slow play without sounding like an jerk? I'm just so used to playing 1v1 competitive matches, that sitting through a multiplayer turn cycle with casual players is pretty unbearable, it's really soured my play experience lately. Any advice?
Does it just feel slow, or are there definite examples of times where players were taking far longer than they should?
About a two years ago we had two guys join our group who were new/returning, the biggest thing that had made a change in speed of turns is actually deck construction
They learned how to better make their decks, so that they had an overall goal for each turn
from my experience they tank every turn, like they haven't been planing their turn at all,
All these guys have solid decks, they just lack that time awareness that competitive play   forces you to have
One still takes 100 years to fetch though, so we always tell him to start searching at the end of his turn and then he can just say it was the end of turn of the guy before him

Depending on the group, teasing might work, but I think maybe do some 2 headed giant could help, in that you can show them your process as you are a team, like, as other teams are going you just start talking strategies and such

The main thing to remember is that they're trying to play their best. Approach a conversation that way. They're not trying to be slow, they're trying to improve, to win, to make the best plays. It's useful to keep their desires in mind to prevent things from getting antagonistic
You might also try other formats like modern to try and get them to speed up, even then, most of it is probably going to be a conversation

If you acknowledge their goals, they can acknowledge yours: "i haven't been having a lot of fun in our games lately. The pace of the game really brings me out of the fun. And I feel super awkward bringing it up because I know you're trying to make your best move, and it's a complicated game that requires a lot of thought. But I gotta say something because I'm just not having fun anymore..."
It also sounds like you want to play Legacy or the like since 1v1 Commander is a very different beast vs multiplayer. I agree that these guys are still.learning their decks and play.
It could be as simple as "we can try to get better by being deliberate, or by trying things until it is right, and jam more gams"
Some of my best learning moments for playing is just going saying to the table "yolo" and going for it
My friends have learned to be wary of the phrase

Strongly disagree with the timer--it's more likely to make people feel guilty or nervous about slow play, and that'll make them feel bad. You're not trying to make your play group feel bad, you're trying to have a heart-to-heart
It also punishes players on the wrong turn for interaction

I play most competitive formats already, I still want to play commander, just faster. It also is my problem too, I just am attuned to these things more, my friend may not even realize how slow they are playing. Thanks for the advice guys JOEY's points sound like they may be effective for my group.
